### The Any Type

`any` disables type checking and allows any operation:

```typescript
let value: any = 42;
value = "hello"; // OK
value = true; // OK
value.toUpperCase(); // OK (no type checking)
```

Avoid `any` when possible as it defeats the purpose of TypeScript.

### The Unknown Type

`unknown` is the type-safe counterpart of `any`. You cannot perform operations on `unknown` without type narrowing:

```typescript
let value: unknown = 42;
value = "hello"; // OK
// value.toUpperCase(); // Error: Object is of type 'unknown'

// Must narrow type first
if (typeof value === "string") {
  console.log(value.toUpperCase()); // OK
}
```

### The Never Type

`never` represents values that never occur. It is the return type for functions that always throw or have infinite loops:

```typescript
function throwError(message: string): never {
  throw new Error(message);
}

function infiniteLoop(): never {
  while (true) {}
}
```

### Comparison

| Type | Assignable to anything? | Operations allowed? | Use case |
|------|------------------------|-------------------|----------|
| `any` | Yes | Yes | Migration from JS |
| `unknown` | No | No (without narrowing) | Type-safe APIs |
| `never` | Yes (to nothing) | N/A | Exhaustive checks |

> **Key Point:** Prefer `unknown` over `any` when you don't know the type.

codeExample:
// any - avoid
let flexible: any = 10;
flexible = "text";
flexible = true;

// unknown - preferred
let safe: unknown = "hello";
if (typeof safe === "string") {
  console.log(safe.length);
}

// never - exhaustive check
type Shape = "circle" | "square";
function area(shape: Shape): number {
  switch (shape) {
    case "circle": return 1;
    case "square": return 2;
    default: throw new Error("Unreachable"); // shape is never here
  }
}
